#: src/rust-2018/rustdoc/documentation-tests-can-now-compile-fail.md:1
msgid "Documentation tests can now compile-fail"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustdoc/documentation-tests-can-now-compile-fail.md:3
msgid ""
"![Minimum Rust version: 1.22](https://img.shields.io/badge/"
"Minimum%20Rust%20Version-1.22-brightgreen.svg)"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustdoc/documentation-tests-can-now-compile-fail.md:5
msgid "You can now create `compile-fail` tests in Rustdoc, like this:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustdoc/documentation-tests-can-now-compile-fail.md:7
msgid ""
"````\n"
"/// ```compile_fail\n"
"/// let x = 5;\n"
"/// x += 2; // shouldn't compile!\n"
"/// ```\n"
"# fn foo() {}\n"
"````"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/rustdoc/documentation-tests-can-now-compile-fail.md:15
msgid ""
"Please note that these kinds of tests can be more fragile than others, as "
"additions to Rust may cause code to compile when it previously would not. "
"Consider the first release with `?`, for example: code using `?` would fail "
"to compile on Rust 1.21, but compile successfully on Rust 1.22, causing your "
"test suite to start failing."
msgstr ""
